Implementation Progress (2026-07)
- Named resident groups (`named_groups`) as a shared foundation, plus group blackouts (`blackouts`): whole groups off call for a window and, by default, the day before; compensated by default — weights untouched, so the ledger's no-catch-up policy issues no credit and the shortfall is repaid via carryover, never excused.
- Shift-type load reductions (`reductions`): per-person hard caps at factor × fair share of chosen labels inside a window (never infeasible; Unfilled absorbs), with per-entry modes — "work less now" (total/NF targets lowered, whole shortfall repaid later) or "keep full share" (other shift types compensate in-block).
- Fairness table (counts + points per label, targets/devs, prior/cumulative ledger columns, notes, CSV) alongside the text log; per-call audit table; in-app editable carryover ledger; ledger JSON now accumulates per-label points/counts (informational; carryover stays on total/weekend/night_float; backward compatible).
- Excel/CSV import of monthly availability requests (template, tolerant header/name/date parsing, per-row validated preview) applying as compensated leaves.
- Soft shift preferences (`preferred_shifts`, `preferred_day_type`): a lowest objective tier under a K = 2·D·S + 1 rescale of all fairness weights, so preferences only order exact fairness ties; K = 1 (byte-identical objective) when unused.
- Blackout refinement: the day-before rule blocks only night on-calls (`is_night_call`: thu_weekend and not night_float — the roster's existing night marker) and night float is excluded from blackouts entirely; blocking moved to slot level (`_blocked_slot_indices`).
- Rotator shift coverage at entry (multiselect in the rotator editor feeding `exempt_shifts`); groups/blackouts/reductions confirmed to apply to rotators.
- Avoid pairs (`avoid_pairs`): a hard same-day separation constraint per pair (never infeasible alone, fairness targets untouched), UI-gated behind an access code as deliberate friction.
- Fairness-outcome audit (`scripts/fairness_audit.py`) with two fixes: (1) coverage now dominates the objective (`objective_weights` gives `W_UNFILLED = max_slot_points × Σ deviation weights + 1`), so a fillable slot is never dropped to reduce deviation; (2) the spec's per-label balance is auto-enforced (`_auto_label_targets` sets `target_label` for every eligible resident, feeding the existing `dev_label` tier), gated by `LABEL_TARGET_MAX_CELLS` and skipping reduction- and preference-covered residents. Verified: small/mid problems reach equal totals AND equal per-shift-type mix; multi-block ledger repays blackout/reduction debt to convergence.
- Per-cap carryover policy (`max_total_excused`): a `max_total` cap now chooses how its shortfall below fair share is treated across blocks. "Compensate later" (default, `False`/absent — the historical behaviour) leaves the shortfall uncredited, so cumulative balancing loads the resident up in later blocks to make it up (correct for a *temporary* cap; a permanent one builds honest, ever-growing debt). "Do not compensate later" (`True`) excuses it: `ledger.block_adjustments` credits the capped resident their `fair − cap` shortfall and debits the residents who absorb it (weighted, sums to zero), so everyone is recorded at fair standing and nobody catches up — the same shape as a perk, which keeps a permanent excused cap from diverging. UI: a "Compensate later" checkbox per cap (③ Advanced → Caps). Covered by `tests/test_ledger.py`.
- Shift closures (`model/closures.py`, `ShiftClosure` = label + window + optional weekdays): a shift stood down on a set of dates (resident shortage, dropped holiday shift). Closed `(date, label)` cells are **reserved** — removed from regular demand, never assigned, never counted as *unfilled*, and outside the point/fairness/ledger pools — and are written into the schedule as `"Closed"`. Threaded through the solver (`_is_regular`/output), `resolve_targets`/`block_adjustments`/`_auto_label_targets` (excluded from pools), fairness reporting (health line shows a closed count; points/counts/coverage skip them), validation (config checks + schedule-rule skip), `config_io` round-trip, and a UI editor (② Dates & rules → Shift closures). Old configs without `closures` load unchanged. Covered by `tests/test_closures.py` and a `closures_scenario` audit case.
- Manual edit gained both non-resident markers per cell: **Unfilled** (a coverage gap — counted against coverage, points reported as unfilled) and **Closed** (unavailable / not staffed — removed from demand, never counted as unfilled, outside points and fairness). `ui/state.py:normalize_edited_schedule` recomputes `df.attrs["closed_cells"]` from the edited grid, so a cell set to `"Closed"` is treated exactly like a configured closure (and reassigning a resident re-opens it) instead of becoming a phantom "Closed" resident. Covered by `tests/test_app.py`.
- Extension point for "cells the regular scheduler does not fill": `model/closures.py:reserved_cell_keys(df)` is the single union (night-float overlay ∪ closed) that every "is this a regular assignment?" check consults — point totals, the unfilled count, min-gap spacing, schedule validation. A future reserved-cell feature tags its cells on `df.attrs` and adds them to that union; the consumers pick it up with no further edits. The solver's `self.reserved_slots` plays the same role inside the model.
- Fixed a cumulative-fairness regression the overlay rework exposed: because a night-float coverer is now recorded as a recurring *uncompensated absence*, the ledger's no-catch-up excused credit — which had been scaled by the whole running total (`block + Σ prior`) and re-applied every block — diverged for any **recurring** excusal (repeated NF coverage, a standing group factor or perk), so the resident doing the *least* work ended up recorded with the *most* and later targets were corrupted. `block_adjustments` now measures the excused credit on **this block only** (`f · p_tot · gap`), which is byte-identical for a first/one-time block (every exact-number and one-time-invariant test unchanged) but stays bounded and correct-direction under recurrence: NF coverers converge to equal cumulative standing instead of running away. Also fixed `update_ledger` dropping the informational `nf_days` duty count when carrying prior entries forward (it now accumulates). Covered by new `tests/test_ledger.py` regressions and a `recurring_nf_ledger` audit scenario.
- Night float reworked into a **separate coverage overlay** (`model/night_float.py:resolve_night_float`) that runs before the regular scheduler. `ShiftTemplate.night_float` now means *eligible*; a per-shift `nf_coverage` pattern (weekdays + include/exclude dates) says which dates the overlay covers, and explicit `nf_assignments` (person, period, labels, rest_days) say who covers them. Covered cells are removed from regular demand and never carry regular points; each coverer's period + rest is fed to the regular solve as an uncompensated leave (`nf_leave_windows`), so weights/`_blocked_day_indices`/ledger all agree with no future catch-up. A coverer only ever covers their own role's NF shifts (empty labels = all of that role's NF shifts); overlay cells ride on `df.attrs` as a serializable `{date-iso: {label: name}}` map. Covered dates with no coverer fall back to regular (advisory). Removed the balanced NF dimension entirely: `target_night_float`/`dev_night_float`, the NF-block/rest constraints, `max_nights` enforcement, and `model/nf_blocks.py`; ledger carryover is now total/weekend only, with an informational `nf_days` duty count. `is_regular_night_call` makes the blackout "night before" rule date-aware (protects regular residents on an NF-eligible night's uncovered dates). Overlay cells are tagged in `df.attrs["nf_cells"]` so fairness/validation/exports/manual-edit treat them as coverage, not regular assignments. Covered by `tests/test_night_float.py` and an `overlay_night_float` audit scenario; old configs/ledgers load unchanged.

